The erroneous code fails because the variable named variable is declared without an initial value. Java requires local variables to be initialized before use. The corrected version assigns a value immediately after declaration.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The next class assigns a new value to the variable and prints the result.

```java
public class AssignValue {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "New content";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The following class concatenates the variable with another string and displays the combined text.

```java
public class ConcatenateString {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello";
        String result = variable + " world";
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```

The final class compares the variable to another string and returns the boolean outcome of that comparison.

```java
public class CompareString {
    public static boolean check(String variable) {
        String target = "Hello world";
        return variable.equals(target);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        boolean result = check(variable);
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```
